social_posts.post_text: Highlight 2023. @just_little_adventure surfing and @gigantesdenazare with @gabrielsamps

No warm up - straight into the action.   This day was crazy. Around 11 am I was flying through the “lineup” , capturing the pretty Nazaré A-Frames that I hadn’t seen in a while. Only one thing was different. The lineup was empty. Shortly after I witnessed a super scary ski wipeout that luckily turned out ok after all. In the afternoon I knew @rafaeltapialewin and @gabrielsamps would be going for a session. So when I came back, the ocean had already gotten a bit messy with increasing on shore wind. However, once in a while a couple of A-Frames came through. I saw Rafael getting a big one while I was setting up the drone. I knew there would only be a handful of waves to catch today so that means no warm up, I need to try and get the shot that I want straight away. I usually take some time to get comfortable with the wave style, wind, wave period, vision/light, wave speed, shore break, back wash, potential dangers and finding out where the main peaks are. I see it as calibrating my brain to the conditions. Straight from launching I felt pretty good flying out there because I had already spent 1 1/2 hours flying that day. While getting closer to the lineup I saw Rafael getting on the rope so I had an idea what this will most likely look like. Since I was still a couple hundred metres away, I knew I would only be able to approach the wave crossing in from the front. Thus, the focus will be on the face of the wave. I have analysed a ton of this type of my shots from throughout this season and I often felt that I lost “momentum”- inconsistency of movement - at some point. The reason is that you fly towards the wave and end up flying backwards. Going straight front to back would result in a point of zero speed, which is unsatisfying for the brain. My two goals were 1) don’t bail out of the wave, 2) stay the f* low when your brain says “go up”. I’m happy how it turned out! 

🏄‍♂️ @rafaeltapialewin 
🏎 @gabrielsamps 
📸 @johannes_hertel

O tow-in é uma modalidade na qual o surfista é rebocado por um Jet-Ski. Esse método permite que o atleta “entre” nas ondas mais cedo do que o normal e consiga dropar aquelas que seriam impossíveis apenas na remada.

Venha presenciar os melhores surfistas do mundo desafiando as maiores ondas e mostrando suas manobras de tirar o fôlego! 🌊🌟

Mais uma competição que coloca o Rio de Janeiro no calendário do surfe mundial 🌎🏆

O evento conta com apoio do #GovRJ através da @esportegovrj, por meio da Lei Estadual de Incentivo ao Esporte 🤝✨
